The Nautilus DevOps teams is planning to set up a Grafana tool to collect and analyze analytics from some applications. They are planning to deploy it on Kubernetes cluster. Below you can find more details.
1.) Create a deployment named grafana-deployment-nautilus using any grafana image for Grafana app. Set other parameters as per your choice.
2.) Create NodePort type service with nodePort 32000 to expose the app.
You do not need to make any configuration changes inside the Grafana app once deployed; just make sure you can access the Grafana login page.

Note: The kubectl utility on the jump-host has been configured to work with the Kubernetes cluster.
solution:
First, let me check if we have a namespace to deploy to, or I'll use the default namespace:
kubectl get namespaces

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: grafana-deployment-nautilus
  labels:
    app: grafana
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: grafana
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: grafana
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: grafana
        image: grafana/grafana:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 3000
          name: grafana
        env:
        - name: GF_SECURITY_ADMIN_PASSWORD
          value: "admin"  # Default password for testing
        resources:
          requests:
            memory: "256Mi"
            cpu: "200m"
          limits:
            memory: "512Mi"
            cpu: "500m"
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: grafana-service-nautilus
  labels:
    app: grafana
spec:
  type: NodePort
  ports:
  - port: 3000
    targetPort: 3000
    nodePort: 32000
    protocol: TCP
  selector:
    app: grafana

kubectl apply -f grafana-deployment.yaml
kubectl get deployments
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc
kubectl get svc grafana-service-nautilus

kubectl describe svc grafana-service-nautilus
To access the Grafana login page, you would use:

URL: http://<node-ip>:32000

Default username: admin

Default password: admin (or whatever was set in the environment variable)

If you want to get the node IP where the pod is running:

bash
kubectl get nodes -o wide
And to get more details about the Grafana pod:

bash
kubectl get pods -l app=grafana
kubectl logs -l app=grafana
Summary of what was created:

Deployment: grafana-deployment-nautilus

Uses grafana/grafana:latest image

Single replica

Port 3000 exposed

Environment variable set for admin password

Service: grafana-service-nautilus

Type: NodePort

NodePort: 32000

Maps port 3000 (container) to port 32000 (node)

The Grafana instance is now deployed and accessible via port 32000 on any node in the cluster. You should be able to access the Grafana login page using the node's IP address and port 32000.

